Exercise 2: Regression and model validation

####Description of analysed data

The aim of this study was to set light on the relationship between learning approaches and students’ achievements in an introductory statistics course in Finland.

The data set (N = 166) used in this report consisted of 7 variables: Gender, Age, attitude, Deep approach, Surface approach, Strategic approach and total points. The participants were 17-55-years-olds (mean = 25.5) and 66 % of them were Female.

Read more about the used scales and variables from here

R script for graphical overview of the data:

library()

Creating a regression model with explanatory variables

I chose surf, deep and attitude as the predicted variables for this exercise. Total points were my dependent variable.

Bellow you can find model fit indexes.

# creating a regression model with multiple explanatory variables
my_model <- lm(points ~ attitude + deep + surf, data = analysisdata)

# printing out a summary of the model
summary(my_model)

Interpretation of the model fit

The indexes above show that the model in not working as it is. F-statistic’s p-value is greater than 0.05 which means that the overall model is not significant. The only working predicted variable seems to be attitude.

Deep and surf didn’t have significant relationship with the dependent variable. They were removed from the model bellow. Since there is only one predicted variable now, the overall model fit is still not significant.

# creating a regression model
my_model2 <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = analysisdata)

Results of the regression analysis

Seems like only attitude predicts overall exam points. Good attitude predicts high exam points.The multiple of R squared of the model shows that 19% of the variation is points is explained by the attitude.

Residuals vs Fitted values, Normal QQ-plot and Residuals vs Leverage

As you can see bellow Residual vs. Fitter points spread randomly. Normal Q-Q plot points fits quite well to the line which indicates that the model is normally distributed. There are no outliners standing out in Residuals vs. Leverage plot.

Exploratory analysis

I chose following variables to do exploratory analysis: current health status (health), number of past class failures (failures), going out with friends (goout) and quality of family relationships (famrel).

My hypothesis (based on my personal speculations):

H1. Good health status is negatively related to high alcohol consumption.

H2. Number of past class failures is positively related to high alcohol consumption.

H3. Going out with friends increases the risk for high alcohol consumption.

H4. Higher quality of family relationships reduce the risk for high alcohol consumption.

Exploring the the distributions of the chosen variables and their relationships with alcohol consumption
Health status

Despite of what was assumed above (H1), There are not big differences in health status between the high alcohol users and the others when we look at the boxplots. The Chi-squared test also indicates that there is no statistically significant relationship between these two variables (p > .05).

g1 <- ggplot(alc_data, aes(x = high_use, y = health))
g1 + geom_boxplot() + ylab("Health status")

prop.table(table(alc_data$health, alc_data$high_use))

Logistic regression

Based on the model bellow, only going out with friends and family relationships are significant predictors of high alcohol consumption. Hypothesis H1 and H2 are rejected. Health and failures variables will be moved from the model for further analysis.

model_1 <- 
  glm(high_use ~ 
        health + failures + goout + famrel,
      data=alc_data)
summary(model_1)

As seen in the new model bellow, one step increase in going out increases the odds of high alcohol usage by 15% and having good family relations decrease the odds by 15%.

model_3 <- 
  glm(high_use ~ 
        famrel + goout,
      data=alc_data)

OR <- exp(coef(model_3))
CI <- exp(confint(model_3))
## Waiting for profiling to be done...

Cross tabulation

As seen bellow, the number of inaccurately classified individuals is around 27%. The model estimates that 11% would be high alcohol users.

probs <- predict(model_2, type = "response")
alc_data <- mutate(alc_data, probability = probs)

alc_data <- mutate(alc_data, predicted_high=probability> 0.5)

table(high_use = alc_data$high_use, prediction = alc_data$predicted_high) %>% prop.table() %>% addmargins()
##         prediction
## high_use      FALSE       TRUE        Sum
##    FALSE 0.66492147 0.04188482 0.70680628
##    TRUE  0.22513089 0.06806283 0.29319372
##    Sum   0.89005236 0.10994764 1.00000000
ggplot(alc_data, aes(x = probability, y = high_use, col=predicted_high)) +
 geom_point(size=2)

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
 n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
 mean(n_wrong)
}

loss_func(class = alc_data$high_use, prob = alc_data$probability)
## [1] 0.2670157

As seen in the descriptive statics and histograms above, great number of the variables are highly skewed. That’s also the case with the variable of my main interest, crime rates. That means there are low crime rates in generally in Boston.

Next, to see the relationships between the variables, I’m going to plot a correlation matrix. I eliminated all the correlations that were not significant (p > .05 at 95 % confidence level). The eliminated ones are marked with crosses.

cor_matrix<-cor(Boston) %>% round(digits = 2)

Next, I’ll create a new categorical variable of the crime rates. I’ll use the quantiles as the break points in the categorical variable. See bellow a table of the new crime variable.

Then, I’ll drop the old crime rate variable and divide the dataset to train and test sets, so that 80% of the data belongs to the train set.

#Save categories of crime rate
bins <- quantile(boston_scaled$crim)

#new variable
crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, labels = c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))
table(crime)

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "orange", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

# predict classes with test data
lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)

# cross tabulate the results
table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)

The plot shows that the high crime rate areas groups together relatively well, but the other groups are more overlapping with each other.

Seems that the access to radial highways separates relatively well the high crime rate group. Summary of the model shows that mean of the access to radial highways-variable is high in the high crime rate group, and lower in the others. The findings indicates that there are more crimes happening in the areas of Boston with easy access to highways.

When we look at the prediction table, we can see that the model groups the high crime rate areas pretty correctly but had more difficulties with the other groups.

Next, I’m going to run the k-means algorithm for different cluster numbers. My maximum number for clusters is 10. Based on the plot bellow, the optimal number of clusters is two.

# determine the best number of clusters
k_max <- 10
# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(Boston, k)$tot.withinss})
# visualize the results
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

# k-means clustering
km <-kmeans(Boston, centers = 2)

# plot the whole Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(Boston, col = km$cluster)

Exercise 5: Clustering and classification

Description of the analysed data

The data set used in these analysis consists of 8 variables (n = 155) and all the variables in the data are continuous. The data combines several indicators from most countries in the world. The variables measure phenomena related to health & knowledge and gender empowerment

Read more about the data from here

Here’s a little glossary to help understand the short terms used in tables:

GNI = Gross National Income per capita

Life.Exp = Life expectancy at birth

Edu.Exp = Expected years of schooling

Mat.Mor = Maternal mortality ratio

Ado.Birth = Adolescent birth rate

Parli.F = Percetange of female representatives in parliament

Edu2.FM = Proportion of females/ males with at least secondary education

Labo.FM = Proportion of females/ males in the labour force

Also, when we look at the ggpairs output and correlation matrix, we can see that there are high positive correlation between Adolescent birth rate and Maternal mortality ratio. Life expectancy at birth correlates negatively with both maternal morality ration and adolescent birth rate. There are also high negative correlation between Expected years of schooling and Adolescent birth rate. On the line with other strong correlations, there are also strong positive correlation between Expected years of schooling and Life expectancy at birth.
